% Projects
\section{Projects}

\subsection{AI-Optimized Low-Power Analog Neural Network Processor (Proposed Final Year Project)}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
  \item Designed a low-power analog \textbf{multiply-and-accumulate (MAC) unit} using CMOS building blocks (Gilbert cell multiplier and summing op-amp) in Cadence Virtuoso/LTspice; characterized linearity, power, and speed. 
  \item Implemented a behavioral model of a small neural network in \textbf{Verilog-A/AMS} and integrated the transistor-level MAC unit into the system for mixed-mode hybrid simulation. 
  \item Validated functionality with test inputs, demonstrated correct neural operation, and compared power consumption against a digital baseline to highlight analog efficiency. 
  \item Documented design flow: transistor-level circuit design, mixed-signal co-simulation, and performance analysis (accuracy, energy savings, scalability). 
  \item Developed strong skills in \textbf{analog/mixed-signal design, neuromorphic hardware, hybrid simulation methodologies, and low-power VLSI techniques}. 
\end{itemize}


\subsection{Low-Power PWM Controller for On-Chip Power Management (Proposed Final Year Project)}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
  \item Designed a mixed-signal \textbf{low-power PWM controller} for DC–DC conversion with programmable frequency (200\,kHz–1\,MHz), fine duty-cycle resolution, and configurable dead-time. 
  \item Implemented analog building blocks (oscillator, comparator, error amplifier) integrated with a lightweight \textbf{digital FSM} for startup, shutdown, and protection control. 
  \item Achieved low quiescent current ($<$10\,µA in standby), jitter $<$1\% of period, and robust closed-loop regulation with phase margin $>$45° (post-layout simulations). 
  \item Completed schematic-to-layout flow: transistor-level design, mixed-signal co-simulation, \textbf{PEX-based verification}, and performance characterization (efficiency, stability, noise) using Cadence and MATLAB/Python. 
  \item Developed strong skills in \textbf{analog/mixed-signal design, low-power techniques, control-loop verification, and PMIC system integration}. 
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Two-Stage CMOS Operational Amplifier Design}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
  \item Designed and simulated a \textbf{two-stage CMOS operational amplifier} with Miller compensation for high gain and frequency stability. 
  \item Achieved open-loop gain $>$70\,dB, unity-gain bandwidth in MHz range, and phase margin $>$60°, while maintaining rail-to-rail output swing and low power consumption. 
  \item Performed full custom design flow: schematic entry, \textbf{DC/AC/transient/noise analyses}, layout implementation, \textbf{DRC/LVS checks}, parasitic extraction (PEX), and post-layout verification. 
  \item Gained expertise in \textbf{analog VLSI circuit design, frequency compensation, layout matching, and performance validation} using Cadence Virtuoso and SPICE simulations. 
\end{itemize}

\subsection{VGA Controller Design using VHDL (640$\times$480 @ 60Hz)\hfill July 2025 -- August 2025}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
  \item Designed and implemented a VGA synchronization controller on FPGA using VHDL, targeting 640$\times$480 resolution at 60Hz refresh rate. 
  \item Developed RTL modules with counters and finite state machines to generate horizontal/vertical sync pulses, pixel timing, and video enable signals. 
  \item Implemented pixel coordinate tracking and conditional rendering of a centered rectangular box with programmable RGB output. 
  \item Achieved 25\,MHz pixel clock division from the input clock and ensured correct video timing (porches, sync pulse, and active video). 
  \item Strengthened skills in \textbf{RTL design, clock-domain management, FPGA timing analysis, and hardware description languages}, relevant to VLSI design. 
\end{itemize}

\subsection{FPGA-Based Memory Game using VHDL\hfill July 2025 -- August 2025}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
  \item Designed and implemented a digital \textbf{memory game (Simon-Says style)} on FPGA using VHDL, based on a finite state machine (FSM). 
  \item Utilized a 50\,MHz input clock and derived lower-frequency timing for LED display, button input handling, and sequence pacing. 
  \item Implemented a \textbf{pseudo-random sequence generator} using Linear Feedback Shift Register (LFSR) to generate LED patterns of increasing length. 
  \item Developed game logic including sequence display, user input verification, win/lose detection, scoring, and progression control. 
  \item Integrated \textbf{LEDs and 7-segment displays} for real-time feedback on game state, score, and user responses. 
  \item Strengthened expertise in \textbf{FSM-based RTL design, pseudo-random generation, timing control, and FPGA hardware prototyping}, directly applicable to VLSI system design. 
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Digital Signal Processing \& Communication Systems}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
  \item Developed comprehensive \textbf{audio processing pipeline} using FFT algorithms for frequency domain analysis, implementing professional spectrograms and magnitude spectrum visualization with Python/Librosa/NumPy.
  \item Designed high-performance \textbf{FIR digital filters} (201 taps, 3\,kHz cutoff) for speech enhancement, successfully removing noise while preserving intelligibility in real audio samples.
  \item Conducted systematic \textbf{sampling theory validation} through downsampling experiments (44.1\,kHz to 5.5\,kHz), demonstrating Nyquist theorem and aliasing effects via detailed spectrogram analysis.
  \item Implemented three \textbf{digital modulation schemes} (ASK, FSK, PSK) for communication systems with configurable parameters, simulating complete transmitter chains for modern wireless applications.
  \item Developed strong skills in \textbf{Python scientific computing, signal processing algorithms, telecommunications theory, and professional data visualization}.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Antenna Design and Simulation using HFSS\hfill June 2025 -- August 2025}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
  \item Designed and simulated multiple antennas (patch at 8.4\,GHz, Yagi-Uda at 13.4\,GHz, dipole at 2.5\,kHz, and monopole at 2.5\,kHz/8.4\,GHz) using Ansys HFSS. 
  \item Analyzed and compared antenna performance across frequency bands, focusing on \textbf{gain, directivity, radiation efficiency, VSWR/return loss, and bandwidth}. 
  \item Demonstrated differences in radiation characteristics: omnidirectional (dipole/monopole) vs.\ directional high-gain (Yagi-Uda) vs.\ moderate directivity (patch). 
  \item Strengthened expertise in \textbf{full-wave EM simulation, impedance matching, radiation pattern analysis, and frequency-dependent optimization}, relevant to RF and VLSI/SoC integration. 
\end{itemize}

\subsection{12-Pulse Rectifier Design and Analysis\hfill August 2025}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
  \item Designed and simulated a \textbf{12-pulse rectifier} using PLECS for high-power conversion applications.  
  \item Analyzed the \textbf{DC output voltage and current waveforms}, highlighting reduced ripple, improved waveform quality, and harmonic suppression compared to conventional 6-pulse rectifiers.  
  \item Evaluated converter performance in terms of output smoothness, harmonic distortion, and power factor, demonstrating suitability for industrial motor drives and HVDC applications.  
  \item Strengthened expertise in \textbf{power electronics simulation, waveform analysis, and converter performance evaluation} using PLECS.  
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Smart Traffic Light System \hfill March 2025 -- April 2025}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
    \item Designed and simulated a smart traffic light control system using Wokwi and ultrasonic sensors to optimize traffic flow based on real-time vehicle density.
    \item Implemented congestion detection logic with dynamic green light timing and integrated sensor calibration, LED control, and serial communication.
    \item Applied embedded systems principles such as digital I/O, memory-efficient logic, and real-time delays to model efficient urban traffic management.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Simulation and Characterization of nMOSFET Behavior Using LTspice \hfill December 2024 -- January 2025}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
    \item Designed a complete nMOSFET circuit in LTspice, incorporating appropriate biasing, power supply, and load resistor. Configured device parameters (e.g., threshold voltage, channel length, and width) based on a standard CMOS process.  
    \item Performed DC sweep analysis to investigate output characteristics (I\textsubscript{D}-V\textsubscript{DS}) across various gate voltages, and used transient simulations to observe switching behavior under pulsed gate input.
    \item Analyzed simulation results to extract key parameters such as threshold voltage (V\textsubscript{th}), transconductance (g\textsubscript{m}), and drain current in saturation, validating against theoretical models for digital and analog applications.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Analyzed the behavior of a CMOS Inverter using Cadence Virtuoso \hfill December 2024 -- January 2025}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
    \item Simulated and analyzed the transient and DC characteristics of a CMOS inverter using Cadence Virtuoso.
    \item Observed key performance metrics, including noise margins, propagation delay, and power dissipation.
    \item Results showed a low-to-high propagation delay of approximately 100 ps and a high-to-low delay of 90 ps, with a power dissipation of 200 µW at V$_{dd}$ = 1.8V. The study provided insights into how transistor sizing and supply voltage impact switching speed and power consumption in VLSI design.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{12-bit Synchronous Up-Counter Design}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,noitemsep]
    \item Conceptualized and implemented a \textbf{12-bit synchronous up-counter} from first principles, applying \textbf{Finite State Machine (FSM)} design methodology to ensure structured and scalable operation.  
    \item Realized the design using \textbf{D Flip-Flops} and optimized combinational logic for precise synchronous clocking and predictable state transitions.  
    \item Engineered the output interface by integrating a \textbf{BCD decoder} and display driver, enabling real-time human-readable visualization of the counter sequence.  
    \item Verified functional correctness and timing integrity through \textbf{Falstad Digital Circuit Simulator}, demonstrating robustness and adaptability for larger counter architectures.  
    \item Highlighted design trade-offs in \textbf{modularity, timing, and expandability}, showcasing applicability in embedded digital systems and VLSI prototyping.  
\end{itemize}

